spec: dc3301
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(decimal)
docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html
provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/decimal.html — decimal: Decimal fixed-point and floating-point arithmetic"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 667 (dc3301): __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__ dict-presence checks for decimal types."
    - "Classes covered: decimal.Decimal, decimal.Context, decimal.DecimalException, decimal.InvalidOperation, decimal.Overflow, decimal.Underflow."
    - "Theme: __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__ dict-presence (in-place /=, //=, %=)."
    - "KEY FINDING: decimal.Decimal does NOT define __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, or __imod__ in its own __dict__: Decimal is immutable; augmented assignment (d /= x, d //= x, d %= x) rebinds the variable to a new Decimal via __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__, not the in-place variants."
    - "Decimal defines __truediv__, __floordiv__, __mod__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__ (forward and reflected arithmetic) but NOT the in-place variants, confirming immutability."
    - "This is consistent with wave 666 (dc3286) where __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__ were all false: the complete set of in-place augmented assignment operators is absent from decimal.Decimal.__dict__."
    - "decimal.Decimal does NOT define __itruediv__: false. Decimal is immutable; d /= x creates a new Decimal via __truediv__, it does not mutate d in place."
    - "decimal.Decimal does NOT define __ifloordiv__: false. Same reason; d //= x rebinds d to a new Decimal via __floordiv__."
    - "decimal.Decimal does NOT define __imod__: false. Same reason; d %= x rebinds d to a new Decimal via __mod__."
    - "decimal.Context does NOT define __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, or __imod__ in its own __dict__: Context is a precision/rounding configuration object, not a numeric operand."
    - "decimal.DecimalException, decimal.InvalidOperation, decimal.Overflow, decimal.Underflow are exception subclasses with no arithmetic protocol defined in their own __dict__."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"
error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __itruediv__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__itruediv__')
#
# decimal.Decimal does NOT define __itruediv__ in its own __dict__: false.
# Decimal is immutable; d /= x rebinds d via __truediv__, not __itruediv__.
# Decimal defines __truediv__, __rtruediv__ but deliberately omits __itruediv__.
# Consistent with wave 666: all in-place operators absent from Decimal.__dict__.
# All decimal classes: false.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table dc3301.itruediv:
  description: "decimal types __itruediv__ dict-presence checks; wave 667"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
